snippet.textDisplay:
Romantic relationships are actually all about ourselves. It's all ego. When we see that person that WE find attractive. When that person has that personality that WE like. It's all about finding someone that fits into the mold and ideals that WE created and look for...It's not even about the other person for who THEY are. We find this person who WE are attracted to - become excited and 'alive' in the shadow of what we think they give us and how they make us feel. Ego, ego, ego. The euphoria of feeling wanted back for the same reasons starts to wear off - the ideals we projected onto that person are seen for what they really are...Except instead of being totally honest with ourselves about all of this we look for another to take their place and re-live the entire thing over and over again.

Even I who is not THAT interested in looks & money and having my number 1 attraction based on intelligence also falls into the ego trap just the same as those only looking at the surface level. Even looking at just intelligence is STILL ego driven just the same.

Once I understood this I could not be in a relationship again - my desire for one vanished after years and years of searching for 'the one'. Sure, I have moments of wanting that connection - but realize in those moments it's really not what I am needing for all of the above reasons. I need myself. That is all.

snippet.textDisplay: He is somewhat like his female counter-part Adele. Her catalog of hit tracks includes plenty of romantic victim songs and so does his. His massively popular album was called "In the Lonely Hour" and the hit single was about a man so desperate for real love he would accept a night spent in the arms of a FWB or something similar. Now he is expressing that yearning again, but this time for a love "to die for". Really nice song, but unfortunately that is exactly the kind of scary need  that men run the opposite direction from so you gotta act like you don't need a damn thing.  I recently saw him interviewed and he expressed comical contempt for Valentine's Day but there was a trace of sadness when the interviewer kept talking about love. For all I know he is secretly partnered to a romantic god, but it seems not. Art is not always a true reflection of the artist's life, but more often than not it is. One can be rich and miserable.  Someone wonderful please marry this divinely talented lad!  Just imagine the heavenly sounds coming from the shower in the mornings!
